Vice President Kamala Harris addressed the recent shooting in Georgia, expressing condolences for the victims and condemning the act of violence. She highlighted that six out of the eight people killed were of Asian descent, and seven were women, emphasizing the rise in hate crimes and discrimination against Asian Americans over the past year. Harris discussed the history of racism, xenophobia, and sexism in America, citing examples such as the mistreatment of Chinese workers during the building of the transcontinental railroad and the internment of Japanese Americans during World War II. She emphasized the importance of treating everyone with dignity and respect and recognized the right of all individuals to be safe and recognized as Americans. Harris pledged to speak out against violence, hate crimes, and discrimination. The article concludes with the introduction of President Joe Biden.